urity configuration as the control plane nodes. They'll use a separate ConfigMap and connect to the existing `es-cluster` headless service for discovery—the new nodes just need their transport addresses to be reachable so other nodes can connect to them once they join the cluster. I'm realizing that node attributes like `node.attr.zone` are static settings that can't be changed dynamically through the API, so I'd need to restart the existing pods after updating the ConfigMap. But Kubernetes won't automatically restart pods when ConfigMaps change—I'd have to manually trigger the restart, which could be disruptive. one at a time, so I need to manually trigger a rolling restart of the StatefulSet after updating the ConfigMap. Since the cluster is green with replicas distributed across nodes, the restart should proceed safely without data loss. ConfigMap updates won't automatically restart the pods, so I'd need to either use `kubectl rollout restart` or manually delete them one at a time. The safest approach with 3 nodes (1 master, all data) and 1 primary + 1 replica is to restart one node at a time to maintain quorum. But looking back at the requirement, I'm wondering if I actually need to update the existing nodes with an attribute at all—maybe the criterion just means the new nodes have a different attribute than the originals, whether that's a new attribute or simply the absence of one.\n\nI'll add attributes to both old and new nodes to be explicit about it. My plan is to update the ConfigMap to add `node.attr.zone: original` to the existing nodes, then do a rolling restart of the StatefulSet. Since we have 1 primary + 1 replica across 2 different nodes, temporarily dropping to 2 nodes during the restart should keep the cluster healthy while Elasticsearch reassigns replicas as needed.\n\nThen I'll create a new ConfigMap for the new nodes with `node.attr.zone: new`, set up the headless service and StatefulSet for the new data nodes, wait for them to join the cluster, configure the `app-data` index to route shards to the new zone, and monitor the shard relocation process.\n\nFor the rolling restart itself, the StatefulSet's `RollingUpdate` strategy with `partition: 0` means updates happen one pod at a time, which should keep things stable.\n\nBut now I'm reconsidering whether the node attribute approach is the best way to handle this. I could instead use allocation rules to control where shards end up—either requiring shards to only exist on nodes with the new zone attribute, or allowing them to exist on nodes with that attribute.\n\nThe `require` approach is cleaner since it guarantees all app-data shards must be on the new nodes. So I'll go with that strategy: label existing nodes with `zone: original`, give new nodes `zone: new`, then set the index routing requirement to force shards onto the new zone.\n\nHere's my execution plan: update the existing config to add the zone attribute, do a rolling restart, create the new data node StatefulSet with its own config and headless service, wait for them to join the cluster, then apply the routing requirement and monitor the shard relocation.\n\nOne important detail—the new data nodes shouldn't include `cluster.initial_master_nodes` since they're not master-eligible and will just discover the cluster through seed hosts. They'll only have data and ingest roles.\n\nWriting the configurations now...","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":600,"cache_read_input_tokens":36213,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":600},"output_tokens":24,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e235e570-3e57-4655-ae9c-aea4649b4f11","uuid":"e18854b2-bbc5-4bf1-9402-e9a2ba92ba3e","request_id":"req_011CcQAyhxkxjTzKFVvTrrhm"}
